## What happened

In .NET 11, **DSA was removed from macOS**. Calling `DSA.Create()` now throws at runtime on macOS. Windows and Linux are unaffected — DSA still works there (though it's considered legacy).

## How to fix it

Since you need to **verify existing legacy signatures**, you have two options:

### Option 1 — Platform-guard DSA (keep verifying legacy sigs on Windows/Linux only)

```csharp
if (OperatingSystem.IsMacOS())
    throw new PlatformNotSupportedException("DSA verification unavailable on macOS");

using var dsa = DSA.Create();
dsa.ImportParameters(legacyPublicKey);
bool valid = dsa.VerifyData(data, signature, HashAlgorithmName.SHA256);
```

### Option 2 — Migrate signatures to a modern algorithm (recommended)

Re-sign data with **ECDSA** or **RSA**, then update verification:

```csharp
using var ecdsa = ECDsa.Create();
bool valid = ecdsa.VerifyData(data, signature, HashAlgorithmName.SHA256);
```

This is the long-term fix — DSA is deprecated industry-wide. If you must support legacy DSA verification on all platforms during a transition period, you could use a third-party crypto library (e.g., Bouncy Castle) that implements DSA in managed code.
